  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_836360978" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/836360978" />
    <a title="Jonathan Pool" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/27950748-jonathan-pool"><img alt="Jonathan Pool" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1484567350p2/27950748.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/836360978?book_show_action=true">Jul 16, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jonathan Pool" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jonathan Pool" href="/user/show/27950748-jonathan-pool">Jonathan Pool</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover " href="/book/show/12892853-moon-tiger">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/27950748-jonathan-pool?shelf=booker-listed">booker-listed</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/27950748-jonathan-pool?shelf=british_irish-contemporary">british_irish-contemporary</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer836360978" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3324180974129067517">Moon Tiger has been the focus of much, renewed, attention since its surprise selection as a Booker 50 decade winner (for 1987- selected by Lemn Sissay).<br/>Penelope Lively has always had her supporters and Moon Tiger is a work of some style and substance that has not dated.<br/>I heard Penelope Lively speak at the Booker 50 and it was a true pleasure to witness her strength, her independence, her lucidity at age eighty five.<br/>It is tempting to ask whether the Claudia Hampton of Moon Tiger is semi autobiogr</span>
  <span id="freeText3324180974129067517" style="display:none">Moon Tiger has been the focus of much, renewed, attention since its surprise selection as a Booker 50 decade winner (for 1987- selected by Lemn Sissay).<br />Penelope Lively has always had her supporters and Moon Tiger is a work of some style and substance that has not dated.<br />I heard Penelope Lively speak at the Booker 50 and it was a true pleasure to witness her strength, her independence, her lucidity at age eighty five.<br />It is tempting to ask whether the Claudia Hampton of Moon Tiger is semi autobiographical. The Egypt setting matches Lively’s own youth. The question of whether first person, narrator - led, fiction is veiled autobiography is a charge often made by interviewers. At The Royal Festival Hall for Booker 50 (July 2018), Lively raised the subject herself and said she had mixed feelings about Claudia, who she said was, emphatically, not her!!<br />The renewed plaudits for Moon Tiger concur that this is a book that has found its time now. It has staying power, it has a life of its own.<br />Lively talked about the inspiration behind it. Her own memories growing up in Cairo, coupled with hours of research spent in the Imperial War Museum archives.<br />It’s a book about the nature of evidence, and of memory.<br /><br />I enjoyed the book, the writing style, very much.<br />The backdrop of war, (Egypt 1940-4), at close quarters, invariably brings an intensity to a love affair; an untrammelled passion, that’s quite unlike the love that develops in ‘normal’ courtship. There’s no time to waste, the abandonment of worry to stay in the moment of love is intoxicating.<br />The similarities of Moon Tiger and <b> The English Patient </b>(the winner of Booker 50) in this respect are obvious. Luxor- “a world of dust and water” (75)<br />Claudia Hampson’s meeting of Tom Southern is intense, conducted at accelerated speed, and you just know it’s going to end up realistically, tragically. The war generation would not have had the inclination to stress about the complicated, convoluted shenanigans that typify today’s marriages, affairs, jealousies.<br />Claudia Hampton is unapologetic, ostensibly cantankerous, as she lies in her hospital bed. She’s not actually difficult or unreasonable, just a woman whose life experiences (and Lively throws in a number of non - war hardships) are such that faced with a cancerous tumour she doesn’t intend to bow out meekly.<br /><br />“If feminism had been around then I’d have taken it up, I suppose;As it was I never felt it’s absence, being a woman seemed to me a valuable extra asset. My gender was never an impediment”(14)? <br /><br />Lively’s characters are not generally nice. Claudia’s ex husband, Jasper is a narcissist, her brother is sly,”Gordon’s intellectual energy is prodigious; his emotional energy is minimal“(24). His wife,Sylvia, is an invisible presence “she has given little trouble. She has devoted herself to children and houses”(23). Families.<br />Penelope Lively punctuates her depictions of people with waspish stings.<br />I was reminded at times of Elizabeth Strout’s <b>My Name is Lucy Barton </b>(2016), also a bedside reveal of family dysfunction. Claudia’s own daughter is an overlooked footnote: “My Lisa was a dull child”(9),<br />Moon Tiger’s “history of the world” reveals itself in a series of flashbacks; the non linear structure is challenging at first, and it’s a book absolutely made for a second, even more fulfilling read.<br />The final third draws back from the excitement, the life and vitality of our narrator’s glorious, albeit brief, years. It’s a facsimile of all our lives that while the end is known (death), we don’t always know when our peak time has arrived.<br />A fine book, and one indeed that has found its place.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3324180974129067517" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


