    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2583267433" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2583267433" />
    <a title="Betsy Robinson" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5149179-betsy-robinson"><img alt="Betsy Robinson" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1404493492p2/5149179.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2583267433?book_show_action=true">Nov 08, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Betsy Robinson" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Betsy Robinson" href="/user/show/5149179-betsy-robinson">Betsy Robinson</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2583267433" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1298823102951880075"><b><i>Moon Tiger</i> by Penelope Lively</b><br/><br/><blockquote>. . . everything can be retrieved, . . . a lifetime is not linear but instant. . . . inside the head, everything happens at once. (68)</blockquote>That quote describes both the plot and structure of this stunning book.<br/><br/>Claudia Hampton is 76 and dying, and as she dies, she tells the story of her world—all its failures, successes, loves (forbidden and lost), peoples, times, and points of view. She jumps from first person to third to different first persons, and it is not the least b</span>
  <span id="freeText1298823102951880075" style="display:none"><b><i>Moon Tiger</i> by Penelope Lively</b><br /><br /><blockquote>. . . everything can be retrieved, . . . a lifetime is not linear but instant. . . . inside the head, everything happens at once. (68)</blockquote>That quote describes both the plot and structure of this stunning book.<br /><br />Claudia Hampton is 76 and dying, and as she dies, she tells the story of her world—all its failures, successes, loves (forbidden and lost), peoples, times, and points of view. She jumps from first person to third to different first persons, and it is not the least bit confusing.<br /><br />I suspect that many of us with decades behind us can relate to this way of recollecting. A color, a sound, anything can set off a memory as real now as it was in the time that it happened. And likewise, within the memory, we may jump to still other associations. I imagine this is the normal way we review our lives: as a kind of jumble of jigsaw pieces that only we understand as a whole picture. And Penelope Lively wrote it, and it is not only comprehensible but moving.<br /><br />What is particularly moving to me is our impermanence: we’re here, then we’re not; events that feel so compelling, all-consuming, and even historic happen, and then they’re gone and only remain in memory until everybody who holds the memory is gone; places are here, then replaced by others or transformed into unrecognizable new ones. This is sad, but it is also a comforting perspective on my life and current times.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="1298823102951880075" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


