    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3961216845" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3961216845" />
    <a title="Chrissie" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/632247-chrissie"><img alt="Chrissie" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1321799585p2/632247.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3961216845?book_show_action=true">Apr 23, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Chrissie" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Chrissie" href="/user/show/632247-chrissie">Chrissie</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=audible-uk">audible-uk</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=bio">bio</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=2021-read">2021-read</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=england">england</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=egypt">egypt</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=hf">hf</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=love">love</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=philo-psychol">philo-psychol</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=mexico">mexico</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=spain">spain</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3961216845" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer315497610312102046">I like what this book is saying----people’s lives are what history is all about. Our lives are inextricably <b>shaped</b> by history. Our lives are <b>the makings</b> of history. Our lives <b>are</b> history.<br/><br/>Death is total absence, but when the person that has died has shaped another person, the dead person’s essence is preserved in the person that remains. Through the living the dead are preserved. Through the living those that are dead continue to exist….at least for a while. This idea is expressed in the book, an</span>
  <span id="freeText315497610312102046" style="display:none">I like what this book is saying----people’s lives are what history is all about. Our lives are inextricably <b>shaped</b> by history. Our lives are <b>the makings</b> of history. Our lives <b>are</b> history.<br /><br />Death is total absence, but when the person that has died has shaped another person, the dead person’s essence is preserved in the person that remains. Through the living the dead are preserved. Through the living those that are dead continue to exist….at least for a while. This idea is expressed in the book, and I like it. With the recent death of my husband, this speaks to me.<br /><br />We are in the head of a seventy-six-year-old woman. She is dying. She looks back on her life. She was born in 1910. Her thoughts jump back and forth in time. Making sense of the timeline is not difficult. She reminisces about her father who died in the First World War. Her lover died in the Second World War. She was employed as a war correspondent stationed in Egypt. She became an author. She and her brother had strong feelings for each other. We meet her daughter and her brother’s wife. History and relationships are the making of the story.<br /><br />I am not giving the book more stars because there are parts, particularly the section on Mexico, Spain and Cortez, that said little to me. <br /><br />Nicolette McKenzie narrates most of the story. Her voice is deep, just as we are told the central character’s voice was. Thomas Judd reads a part at the end—a part that is best read by a man. The narration is very, very well done, so I have given it four stars.<br /><br />Although fiction, the tale has autobiographical content. My next read will be the author’s non-fictional memoir <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/18819095.Ammonites_and_Leaping_Fish_A_Life_in_Time" title="Ammonites and Leaping Fish A Life in Time by Penelope Lively" rel="nofollow noopener">Ammonites and Leaping Fish: A Life in Time</a>. It focuses on old age. How will it compare?<br /><br />We interpret and evaluate books through our own experiences.<br /><br />********************<br /><br />*<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/11797374.How_It_All_Began" title="How It All Began by Penelope Lively" rel="nofollow noopener">How It All Began</a> 2 stars<br />*<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/130028.Moon_Tiger" title="Moon Tiger by Penelope Lively" rel="nofollow noopener">Moon Tiger</a> 3 stars<br />*<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/18819095.Ammonites_and_Leaping_Fish_A_Life_in_Time" title="Ammonites and Leaping Fish A Life in Time by Penelope Lively" rel="nofollow noopener">Ammonites and Leaping Fish: A Life in Time</a> TBR</span>
  <a data-text-id="315497610312102046" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


